    • Method Detail

      • exists

        public static AttributePredicate exists(String attributeName)
        Returns a predicate that matches any element with the given attribute set, regardless of the attribute value. The CSS notation is
        [ attributeName ]
        with no operator.

        For example, the predicate [foo] will match both elements <p foo> and <p foo="bar">.

        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if the given attribute name is not a valid CSS identifier

      • is

        public static AttributePredicate is(String attributeName,
                    String value)
        Returns a predicate that matches any element with the given attribute set to the given value. The CSS notation is
        [ attributeName = "value" ]

        For example, the predicate [foo = "bar"] will match the element <p foo="bar"> but not the element <p foo="hello">

        Parameters:
        value - the expected (unescaped) value
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if the given attribute name is not a valid CSS identifier

      • containsWord

        public static AttributePredicate containsWord(String attributeName,
                              String word)
        Returns a predicate that matches any element with the given attribute set to a value containing the given word. The attribute value is expected to be a whitespace-separated list of words. The CSS notation is
        [ attributeName ~= "word" ]

        For example, the predicate [foo ~= "bar"] will match the elements <p foo="bar"> and <p foo="hello bar world"> but not the element <p foo="babar">.

        Parameters:
        word - the (unescaped) word whose presence in the value is to be tested
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if the given attribute name is not a valid CSS identifier, or if the word contains a whitespace

      • startsWithSubtag

        public static AttributePredicate startsWithSubtag(String attributeName,
                                  String subtag)
        Returns a predicate that matches any element with the given attribute set to the given subtag, or to a value that starts with the subtag followed by a hyphen. The CSS notation is
        [ attributeName |= "subtag" ]

        For example, the predicate [foo |= "bar"] will match the elements <p foo="bar"> and <p foo="bar-hello"> but not the element <p foo="barhello">.

        Parameters:
        subtag - the (unescaped) subtag
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if the given attribute name is not a valid CSS identifier

      • startsWith

        public static AttributePredicate startsWith(String attributeName,
                            String prefix)
        Returns a predicate that matches any element with the given attribute set to a value starting with the given prefix. The CSS notation is
        [ attributeName ^= "prefix" ]

        For example, the predicate [foo ^= "bar"] will match the elements <p foo="bar"> and <p foo="barhello"> but not the element <p foo="hello bar">.

        Parameters:
        prefix - the (unescaped) prefix
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if the given attribute name is not a valid CSS identifier

      • endsWith

        public static AttributePredicate endsWith(String attributeName,
                          String suffix)
        Returns a predicate that matches any element with the given attribute set to a value ending with the given suffix. The CSS notation is
        [ attributeName $= "suffix" ]

        For example, the predicate [foo $= "bar"] will match the elements <p foo="bar"> and <p foo="hello-bar"> but not the element <p foo="bar hello">.

        Parameters:
        suffix - the (unescaped) suffix
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if the given attribute name is not a valid CSS identifier

      • contains

        public static AttributePredicate contains(String attributeName,
                          String string)
        Returns a predicate that matches any element with the given attribute set to a value containing the given string. The CSS notation is
        [ attributeName *= "string" ]

        For example, the predicate [foo *= "bar"] will match the elements <p foo="bar"> and <p foo="hellobarworld"> but not the element <p foo="b-hello-a-world-r">.

        Parameters:
        string - the (unescaped) string
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if the given attribute name is not a valid CSS identifier
